cal and philosophical perspectives. Some contributions are of a theoretical nature, such as when the »problem of translation«, »the enigma of alienity« or »queer theory« are addressed; other contributors throw light on contemporary issues like the integration of Muslims in Norway, identity-forming processes in »Creole« societies or »neo-traditionalist movements« and »identity« in Africa. Moreover, the book deals with »strangers« looked at from an »anthropology of the night«. Special emphasis is placed on how globalization and the rapid spread of ever new technologies of information have generated ever new patterns of inclusion and exclusion, and how these can be theorized.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aCultural pluralismvCongresses. 4aCultural Studies. 4aCultural Theory. 4aCulture. 4aEthnicity. 4aIdentity. 4aPhilosophy of Culture. 4aSocial Constructivism. 4aSocial Inequality. 4aSociology of Culture. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Popular Culture.2bisacsh  aCultural Studies.  aCultural Theory.  aCulture.  aEthnicity.  aIdentity.  aPhilosophy of Culture.  aSocial Constructivism.  aSocial Inequality.  aSociology of Culture.1 aBehrend, Heike, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEriksen, Thomas Hylland, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKohl, Karl-Heinz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMonceri, Flavia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRottenburg, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRottenburg, Richard, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSchnepel, Burkhard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchnepel, Burkhard, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relat